                                 LINES v. 1.0
                         (c) 1991 by Brian S. Minsker



    LINES is a little program I wrote over the course of several months,
    adding various refinements.  The basic algorithm was originally 
    published in Byte Magazine and ported to a GW-BASIC program by Grant
    Irani with additional changes made by Will Fastie back in 1981.

    The current version of LINES was written in Borland's TurboBASIC.  I
    have added support for EGA, VGA, and MCGA color and monochrome systems
    in addition to the original CGA support, autodetection of the video
    adapter, and command line options to allow the user to select other
    video modes (or if the program is unable to determine the type of monitor
    attached to the system).

    To run LINES, simply type:

                            LINES <video display>

    The video display parameter is generally not required.  LINES should
    be able to detect the type of display used by your system and set its
    parameters accordingly.  If for some reason LINES cannot detect your
    display, you will need to use the video display parameter in the 
    command line.  The following parameters may be used (either upper or
    lower case is fine):

         C  = CGA display
         EM = EGA monochrome display
         EC = EGA color display
         VM = VGA monochrome display
         VC = VGA color display
         MM = MCGA monochrome display
         MM = MCGA color display

    Both the MCGA monochrome and color displays show operate as monochrome
    since the 640 x 480 16-color display is not explicitly supported by
    TurboBASIC.  If you have an MCGA color display, you can try to run
    LINES in VGA color mode.  I would be interested in knowing if the MCGA
    color system is capable of running in VGA color mode.  If so, MCGA
    color support will be included in the next revision of LINES.

